<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-495-931  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 495 931.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Oct 9 1990 v4 n34 p8(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Font fracas ebbing; TrueImage stirs little user enthusiasm.andO;(Microsoft Corp.'s TrueImage page description language) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pfiffner, Pamela.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (product introduction)Apple Computer Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    MSFT; AAPL.andO;Product:   TrueImage (Printer software) (product introduction)Truetype (Computer font) (design and construction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionPage Description LanguagesCompatible Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Pamela PfiffnerandM;San Jose, Calif.andP;  -- A year after the first volley was fired in The FontWars, an uneasy peace lay over the Seybold Computer Publishing Conference andamp;Exposition here last week.andP;  But as the smoke clears, issues about Apple'sTrueType font technology and Microsoft Corp.'s TrueImage page-descriptionlanguage remain cloudy.andM;Microsoft announced that TrueImage had begun shipping to printer OEMs.andO;Microtek Lab Inc. of Torrance, Calif., and LaserMaster Technologies Inc. ofMinneapolis both showed TrueImage printers, but the products failed to stirany significant reaction apart from curiosity.andM;&quot;What does TrueImage bring to the party?andP;  Nothing,&quot; said Tony Bove, editor ofBove andamp; Rhodes Report on Desktop Publishing and Multimedia.andP;  &quot;There's notechnological advantage.andP;  Price and performance gains may have been true ayear ago but not today.&quot;andM;Attendees were less certain about TrueType.andP;  At session after session, usersquestioned representatives of Apple, Microsoft and Adobe Systems Inc. aboutTrueType and Adobe Type 1 compatibility.andP;  &quot;Things are going to work the sameway,&quot; said Jim Stoneham, TrueType product manager, in a refrain repeated overand over again.andP;  Apple also reiterated that Adobe Type Manager will work withTrueType.andM;Cal Bauer, Microsoft printer business unit general manager, said Adobe wouldincorporate the TrueType rasterizer into PostScript.andP;  Adobe CEO John Warnockhad no comment, but said such an approach would not be best for high-endcustomers.andM;For now, users are going to have to take Apple's word that integration of thetwo standards would be seamless.andP;  According to Stoneham, a stable beta ofTrueType will ship to developers this month and to end users with System 7.0in 1991.andP;  It also will be part of Windows 3.1.andP;  Some TrueType features, suchas non-linear scaling, will miss the first release of System 7.0.andM;As at last September's show, the keynote speakers were Warnock, Microsoft CEOBill Gates and NeXT CEO Steve Jobs.andP;  In contrast to last year when the triosat together on the stage, last week they sat in the audience and came up onstage one at a time.andM;Warnock acknowledged that opening the Type 1 standard was to Adobe'sadvantage.andM;&quot;We opened fonts, and there are more out there than ever before, and we'remaking more money off fonts than ever before, so everybody's happy,&quot; he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>